<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="343" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1436,150,393]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,150,176]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">Description</emphasis>
(
<specimenCount box="[353,438,150,177]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343" type="male">5 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[491,598,150,176]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343" type="female">2 females</specimenCount>
measured). Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[884,966,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 94–95" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1747,1771]" captionTargetBox="[174,1411,469,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-151@38.[158,1429,453,1724]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 94–95. Trichotichnus hamulipenis sp. n., habitus. 94, nominotypical subspecies (above Bapo); 95, T. hamulipenis nepalensis ssp. n. (holotype). Scale bar = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781755" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781755/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">Fig. 95</figureCitation>
. On average, body smaller (length 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.15" metricValueMax="9.5" metricValueMin="8.8" pageId="42" pageNumber="343" unit="mm" value="9.15" valueMax="9.5" valueMin="8.8">8.8–9.5 mm</quantity>
, mean = 9.3), elytra relatively narrower and longer (EL/EW 1.46–1.55, mean = 1.52, and EL/PL 2.67–3.01, mean = 2.86), pronotum in central portion coarsely or finely punctate, elytral preapical sinuation (
<figureCitation box="[1255,1337,222,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 96–97" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1168,1192]" captionTargetBox="[153,1425,777,1137]" captionTargetId="figure-266@39.[153,1434,777,1145]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 96–97. Trichotichnus hamulipenis sp. n., elytral apex. 96, nominotypical subspecies; 97, T. hamulipenis nepalensis ssp. n. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781757" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781757/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">Fig. 97</figureCitation>
) in most specimens slightly deeper and internal sac of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[776,871,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 98–105" captionStartId="40.[151,264,1637,1661]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,964,1605]" captionTargetId="figure-323@40.[151,1436,957,1614]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 98–105. Trichotichnus hamulipenis sp. n.: 98–102, nominotypical subspecies (98–100, holotype; 101 &amp; 102, Cikai); 103–105, T. hamulipenis nepalensis ssp. n. (holotype). 98 &amp; 103, terminal lamella of aedeagus; 99, 100, 104 &amp; 105, median lobe of aedeagus; 101, gonocoxite; 102, laterotergite, gonosubcoxite, and gonocoxite. Dorsal (98, 100, 103 &amp; 105), lateral (99, 101 &amp; 104) and ventral (102) views. a, apical spiny patch. Scale bars: A = 0.5 mm (98, 101–103), B = 1.0 mm (99, 100, 104 &amp; 105)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6781759" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6781759/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">Fig. 105</figureCitation>
) with distinct curved spiny patch (
<emphasis box="[1258,1272,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">a</emphasis>
) in apical portion near apical spine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1178,330,357]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1436,150,393]" box="[199,1178,330,357]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,330,356]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of this subspecies is referring to the country where it was found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,992,366,393]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1436,150,393]" box="[199,992,366,393]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,366,392]" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">Distribution.</emphasis>
Widespread in 
<collectingCountry box="[528,595,366,392]" name="Nepal" pageId="42" pageNumber="343">Nepal</collectingCountry>
at altitudes of about 
<quantity box="[830,988,366,393]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="42" pageNumber="343" unit="m" value="2100.0" valueMax="2400.0" valueMin="1800.0">1800–2400 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
